ce:section.ce:para:
In the course of experiment, a common reagent, namely FeCl3, came into our attention, and we found for the first time that a certain concentration of FeCl3 solution could effectively shield UV and blue light. The spatial structure diagram of FeCl3 is shown in Fig. 1
                        a. In this structure, each Fe3+ is surrounded by six Cl-, forming an octahedral coordination environment. These octahedrons are connected together by common edges, forming a complex three-dimensional network structure. The chemical and crystal structures of FeCl3 were analyzed by FTIR and XRD (Fig. 1b and c). Diagram of light transmission process in FeCl3 solution is shown in Fig. 1d. When viewed by the naked eye, high-energy short wavelength light (UV and blue light) is converted into long-wavelength light (yellow and green light), as shown in Fig. 1e. Different heights (volumes) of FeCl3 solutions (0.35 M) were used to shield UV LED (350 nm) and blue LED chips (460 nm). As can be seen from Fig. 1e, when different heights (volumes) of FeCl3 solutions shield the UV LED, the light intensity emitted by the UV LED is significantly reduced, changing from purple to yellow, which indicates that the UV light is absorbed and converted. Even the smallest height (volume) of FeCl3 solution can effectively shield UV light. When different heights (volumes) of FeCl3 solution block the blue LED, the light intensity emitted by the blue LED is significantly weakened. when the volume of FeCl3 solution is small (10 mL and 20 mL), the blue light cannot be effectively shielded. When the volume of FeCl3 solution is increased to 30 mL, the harsh blue light can be completely blocked and converted into non-harsh green light. Meanwhile, we use different concentrations of FeCl3 solutions (30 mL) to shield UV and blue LEDs (Fig. 2
                        ). It can be observed that all concentrations of FeCl3 solutions can effectively screen the UV light, and the color is converted from purple to yellow light. The low-concentration FeCl3 solution cannot effectively shield the blue light, while the high-concentration FeCl3 solution can effectively screen the blue light and convert the harsh blue light into non-harsh green light. Video S1 demonstrates the optical shielding and conversion performance of FeCl3 solutions at different concentrations. The absorption and transmittance spectra of FeCl3 solutions with different concentrations are shown in Fig. S1. As shown in Fig. S1a, the entire absorption spectrum of FeCl3 solutions extend from the UV to blue light region of visible light. The intensity of absorption peaks in UV and blue light region increases with the increase of Fe3+ concentration. As can be seen from Fig. S1b, three concentrations of FeCl3 solution can effectively shield UV and HEBL, and the UV and HEBL shielding ability increases with the increase of solution concentration.
